               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-230-person1900">
                  DANIEL 
                  SRIMPTON
               <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1900" type="surname" value="SRIMPTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1900" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1900" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18300916-230-viclabel1171" type="occupation">gardener</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-230-victim1899 t18300916-230-viclabel1171"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18300916-230-crimeloc1172">Hammersmith</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-230-crimeloc1172" type="placeName" value="Hammersmith"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-230-crimeloc1172" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-230-off1169 t18300916-230-crimeloc1172"></join>. On the evening of the 21st of August I missed this property from my bed-room; I had seen them safe at eight o'clock in the morning - the prisoner lived four or five doors off.</p>

               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CHURCHILL. Q. How long was it before you saw them again? A. The same evening, at the constable's house - my window was a little a jar - the flower-pots were removed, the window put up, and the things taken out.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-230-person1901">
                  JAMES 
                  COOK
               <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1901" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1901" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1901" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am constable of Hammersmith. One Saturday, a little before three o'clock, one of my neighbours next door, called me out, and said he suspected something was going on; I went, and saw the prisoner, who had just left one of the witnesses; I asked what he had been selling, he said a black coat; I took him back, and the witness showed me these things; I said, "I suspect you did not get them honestly, I shall take you to your father;" he said, "Don't do that, I will tell you where I got them;" he pulled out this pillow-case, and said,"Martin was with me;" but I went and brought them face to face, and proved that Martin had not been near the place.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-230-person1902">
                  SAMUEL 
                  AYRES
               <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1902" type="surname" value="AYRES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1902" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-230-person1902" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I met the prisoner in the road - he offered me these things for sale, and I gave him 2s. 3d. for them - he said at first, he had been carrying some fish out for a gentleman who gave them to him.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going up the grove, and these things laid under the wall - this man said he would buy it.</p>
               <p>
